  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={Math.abs(g - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(2)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={Math.abs(row.dr - discountRate) < 0.001 && Math.abs(sensitivityGrowth[i] - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & What This Model Misses</h2>
  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pricing Power:</strong> Consistent ability to push price increases above inflation could lead to higher margins than modeled.</li>
    <li><strong>M&A Activity:</strong> Strategic tuck-in acquisitions could drive non-organic growth beyond the modeled rate.</li>
    <li><strong>Environmental Solutions:</strong> Expansion in recycling and renewable energy segments may yield higher growth and margins.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High Capital Intensity:</strong> Waste management requires continuous, heavy capital expenditures (trucks, landfills), which can drag down Free Cash Flow if costs spike.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Pressures:</strong> Stricter environmental regulations at local or federal levels could increase compliance costs.</li>
    <li><strong>Economic Slowdown:</strong> While resilient, a severe economic downturn can reduce commercial and industrial waste volumes.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples reflect market sentiment. A DCF forces explicit assumptions about the business's actual cash-generating power, helping to anchor value to fundamentals rather than market moods.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. All investments carry risk, and this model relies on assumptions that may not materialize. Always perform your own due diligence.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

